                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12497.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to Mexico.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 15, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>162. Resignation General Huerta and his departure will greatly simplify matters.
                    We take it for granted that the new President will immediately enter into
                    negotiations with Carranza for the peaceful transfer of authority. No other
                    course seems open. This Government will use its influence to bring the parties
                    together. You will please so advise Carbajal if opportunity presents itself and
                    he desires to know this Government’s position. Congratulate him upon the
                    patriotism which leads him to lend his assistance towards the restoration of
                    order.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
